8–1303":"1278–1303","1273–1375":"1273–1375","1303–1365":"1303–1365","1252–1278":"1252–1278","1250–1278":"1250–1278","about 1272":"about 1272","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1303":"1303","1278":"1278","about 1303":"about 1303","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","about 1278":"about 1278","about 1297":"about 1297","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Presteigne with Discoed, Radnorshire, Wales":"Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bole House, Glovers Meaton Bradeley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wever","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German and Dutch: occupational name for a weaver, Middle Low German <i>wever</i>, Middle Dutch <i>wever(e)</i>. Compare   Weber  .","English: variant of   Weaver  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Weber","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a weaver, Middle High German <i>wëber</i>, German <i>Weber</i>, an agent derivative of <i>weben</i> ‘to weave’. This form of the surname is also established in many other parts of Europe, notably in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, and the Netherlands. In Hungary it is mostly spelled <b>Wéber</b> and <b>Véber</b>. In Russia, Slovenia, Czechia, Slovakia, and Croatia it is (also) established in the Slavicized form   Veber  , which is in Czechia also spelled <b>Vebr</b>. Compare   Waber  ,   Weaber  ,   Weaver  ,   Webber  , and   Webre  .","History: As a name of ultimately Swiss German origin the surname <i>Weber</i> is also established among the American Mennonites. However, descendants of the early Mennonite settlers, who came to PA in the early 18th century, mostly bear the Americanized form of the name (see   Weaver  )."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Humphrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Humphry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":18,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Humphrey Wever ap Ieuan was born about 1272, in Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales, his father, Ieuan ap Madoc, was 22 and his mother, Eva verch Trevor, was 24. He married Joyce verch Llewllyn Jenkin about 1297, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1303, in Shropshire, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1272–1303":"umbes 1272–1303","1272–1303":"1272–1303","1278–1303":"1278–1303","1273–1375":"1273–1375","1303–1365":"1303–1365","1252–1278":"1252–1278","1250–1278":"1250–1278","about 1272":"umbes 1272","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1303":"1303","1278":"1278","about 1303":"umbes 1303","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","about 1278":"umbes 1278","about 1297":"umbes 1297","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Presteigne with Discoed, Radnorshire, Wales":"Presteigne, Radnorshire, Wales","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bole House, Glovers Meaton Bradeley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1272–1303":"noin 1272–1303","1272–1303":"1272–1303","1278–1303":"1278–1303","1273–1375":"1273–1375","1303–1365":"1303–1365","1252–1278":"1252–1278","1250–1278":"1250–1278","about 1272":"noin 1272","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1303":"1303","1278":"1278","about 1303":